00:23:19,144 --> 00:23:24,508
and I've had such a good time with them that I have spent money and I don't feel at all bad.

382
00:23:24,508 --> 00:23:28,231
I wish I could name this game because it actually has good UX.

383
00:23:28,231 --> 00:23:31,033
It's one of the few free-to-play games that does it well.

384
00:23:31,033 --> 00:23:32,014
Right, so what does this mean for us?

385
00:23:32,014 --> 00:23:32,634
So if you're a UI or UX designer,

386
00:23:42,226 --> 00:23:47,707
you should discuss the matter of ethics,

387
00:23:47,707 --> 00:23:49,668
or rather the lack of a code of ethics,

388
00:23:49,668 --> 00:23:53,009
because the lack of code of ethics

389
00:23:53,009 --> 00:23:54,989
is kind of the reason why people get away

390
00:23:54,989 --> 00:23:56,269
with all these things.

391
00:23:56,269 --> 00:24:01,371
A lot of the reason why these practices are so common

392
00:24:01,371 --> 00:24:02,451
is because the company,

393
00:24:02,451 --> 00:24:03,491
they set their values more on

394
00:24:11,049 --> 00:24:13,852
getting monetization or getting,

395
00:24:13,852 --> 00:24:19,337
squeezing out the final penny from quote-unquote whale users.

396
00:24:19,337 --> 00:24:22,000
I really don't like that term, but it's true.

397
00:24:22,000 --> 00:24:26,605
And sometimes you kind of have to stand your ground.

398
00:24:26,605 --> 00:24:27,806
I know it's difficult.

399
00:24:27,806 --> 00:24:29,889
Like I think I've been there where I feel like

400
00:24:29,889 --> 00:24:31,170
I don't really want to do this,

401
00:24:31,170 --> 00:24:32,491
but you kind of have to follow orders.

402
00:24:32,491 --> 00:24:33,713
But sometimes if you...

403
00:24:35,166 --> 00:24:42,054
if you stay in your case strong enough and kind of stand together, maybe I'm being a bit romantic

404
00:24:42,054 --> 00:24:49,943
about this, I don't know, the power of friendship, yay! Hopefully it will become less commonplace.

405
00:24:51,628 --> 00:25:02,371
So you have to ask yourself as a UX designer though, what you design, does it manipulate players or does it aid them and let them feel secure about their knowledge and decisions?

406
00:25:02,371 --> 00:25:14,393
People don't like feeling out of control and as UX designers we do persuade players to do certain things, but persuading shouldn't be manipulating.

407
00:25:16,071 --> 00:25:23,179
And of course there's always ways to design for the mutual benefit of players and the game.

408
00:25:23,179 --> 00:25:29,687
Video games is still a business, but that doesn't mean you should

409
00:25:29,687 --> 00:25:35,013
exploit people for the sake of monetary gain.

410
00:25:38,211 --> 00:25:44,394
And if you're a company, it would be great if you could ensure the UX conveys company values.

411
00:25:44,394 --> 00:25:50,856
If you remember what I said earlier, you have a bad experience, you think badly of the game,

412
00:25:50,856 --> 00:25:56,039
and you start thinking badly of that company, and soon people are just like,

413
00:25:56,039 --> 00:25:59,280
God, video games, all they do is waste your money and waste your time.

414
00:25:59,280 --> 00:26:03,782
When in fact that's not true. I'm pretty sure everybody in this room knows that's not true.

415
00:26:05,164 --> 00:26:08,967
So, it'd be great if companies could facilitate

416
00:26:08,967 --> 00:26:11,810
an environment that allows for the refusal

417
00:26:11,810 --> 00:26:14,072
of unethical requests.

418
00:26:14,072 --> 00:26:16,153
Sometimes things happen, and sometimes people are like,

419
00:26:16,153 --> 00:26:18,315
wait, this gets money, because that's metrics.

420
00:26:18,315 --> 00:26:20,918
You know, metrics shows that it works.

421
00:26:20,918 --> 00:26:24,541
Sure, it does work, but at what cost?

422
00:26:24,541 --> 00:26:27,464
It feels a little bit like selling your soul to the devil.

423
00:26:29,542 --> 00:26:31,384
different companies have different priorities,

424
00:26:31,384 --> 00:26:34,389
and there has been people who has left certain companies

425
00:26:34,389 --> 00:26:36,752
because they don't agree with their company policies.

426
00:26:36,752 --> 00:26:38,375
I'm not saying you should quit your jobs or anything,

427
00:26:38,375 --> 00:26:40,959
but you are who you work with.

428
00:26:42,586 --> 00:26:46,348
And finally, use metrics to increase player enjoyment

429
00:26:46,348 --> 00:26:49,150
and not as a tool of manipulation.

430
00:26:49,150 --> 00:26:50,510
I'm pretty sure you can see by now

431
00:26:50,510 --> 00:26:53,912
that I use the word manipulation quite a lot in this.

432
00:26:53,912 --> 00:26:56,674
It's a really fine line between aiding a player

433
00:26:56,674 --> 00:26:58,715
to do what you want or persuading them

434
00:26:58,715 --> 00:27:03,938
or just guiding them and literally manipulating them

435
00:27:03,938 --> 00:27:06,860
to do things that they don't want to do.

436
00:27:06,860 --> 00:27:09,061
So as UX designers, we do have quite a lot of power

437
00:27:09,061 --> 00:27:10,542
and with that much power,

438
00:27:10,542 --> 00:27:12,203
we have quite a bit of responsibility.

